<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-296-681  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 296 681.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Feb 4 1989 v138 n47,771 pZ18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hall of Fame for inventor of imaging. (Patents) (Raymond V.andO;Damadian, inventor of magnetic resonance imaging - MRI) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Edmund L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Raymond V. Damadian, who devised the use of Magnetic ResonanceImaging (MRI) as a medical diagnostic tool, will be inducted intothe National Inventors Hall of Fame by the Patent and TrademarkOffice.andP;  Other members of the Hall of Fame include Thomas Edisonand Alexander Graham Bell.andP;  MRI scanners consist of a cylindricalmagnet that provides an electromagnet field in one direction.andO;When a burst of radio frequency energy is applied in the oppositedirection, the nuclei of some atoms line up, then relax when theenergy is removed, producing a distinct signal.andP;  The results areplotted by computer to create an image.andP;  Dr. Damadian built andtested the first MRI scanner in 1977, but his firm, the FonarCorp, is a minor entity in a market commanded by General Electric,N.V.andP;  Philips and several Japanese firms.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Fonar Corp. (officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    FONR.andO;Topic:     Achievements and AwardsPatentMedical DiagnosisMagnetic DevicesImage GenerationScanning.andO;Person:    Damadian, Raymond (achievements and awards).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>